    "A: 'in order to fill the cistern').",
    "In addition, she stipulates c) that in this case, there is only one thing the man is doing.",
    "Stipulation (c) expresses her alternative to the A-D Principle; and seeing how the descriptions mentioned in (a) fall into the pattern mentioned by (b) is the key to her alternative view: that what the agent really does is not any one of these things but all of them.",
    "That is, she does (a certain teleologically ordered part of) what happens.",
    "First, remember that the principle of unity for an action is, for Anscombe, something people hook onto in the everyday practice of explanation and rationalisation."
